# ACQUISITOR API Environment Variables

## Required Variables

### Database
- `DATABASE_URL` - PostgreSQL connection string
  - Format: `postgresql://user:password@host:port/database`
  - Render: Auto-generated from database service
  - Railway: Auto-generated from PostgreSQL plugin

### Authentication
- `JWT_SECRET` - Secret key for JWT token signing
  - Generate: `openssl rand -hex 32`
  - Must be kept secure

- `GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID` - Google OAuth Client ID
  - Get from: https://console.cloud.google.com/apis/credentials
  - Create OAuth 2.0 credentials for Web application
  - Add authorized redirect URI: `https://your-api-url/auth/google`

- `GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET` - Google OAuth Client Secret
  - Keep this secret!
  - Never commit to git

### Frontend
- `FRONTEND_URL` - Your frontend Vercel URL
  - Example: `https://acquisitor.vercel.app`
  - Used for CORS configuration

## Deployment Instructions

### Option 1: Render (Recommended - matches current frontend config)

1. Push code to GitHub
2. Go to https://dashboard.render.com/
3. Click "New +" → "Blueprint"
4. Connect your GitHub repo
5. Select the `render.yaml` file
6. Render will auto-create:
   - Web service for API
   - PostgreSQL database
7. Add environment variables in Render dashboard:
   - GOOGLE_CLIENT_ID
   - GOOGLE_CLIENT_SECRET
   - FRONTEND_URL (your Vercel URL)

### Option 2: Railway

1. Install Railway CLI: `npm install -g @railway/cli`
2. Login: `railway login`
3. Link project: `railway link`
4. Add PostgreSQL: `railway add --plugin postgresql`
5. Deploy: `railway up`
6. Set environment variables: `railway vars set KEY=value`

## API Endpoints

### Health
- `GET /health` - Health check

### Auth
- `POST /auth/google` - Google OAuth login
- `GET /auth/me` - Get current user
- `POST /auth/logout` - Logout

### Leads
- `GET /leads` - List all leads
- `POST /leads` - Create new lead
- `GET /leads/{id}` - Get single lead
- `PATCH /leads/{id}` - Update lead

### Pipeline
- `GET /pipeline` - Get pipeline stages

### Legacy (for existing frontend)
- `GET /api/scout/leads` - List leads (legacy format)
- `POST /api/scout/leads` - Create lead (legacy format)
- `GET /api/pipeline` - Get pipeline
- `GET /api/activity` - Get activities
- `GET /api/metrics` - Get dashboard metrics

## Testing

After deployment, test with:
```bash
curl https://your-api-url/health
```

Should return:
```json
{
  "status": "healthy",
  "database": "connected",
  "timestamp": "2024-..."
}
```
